<br>
Making of stealth a skill for archers is a solution. Cause more points in bow means it s easier for  us to detect them (and harder for them to hide), and more points in stealth means lower criticals with bow. Or increase our critical and general damage output, cause right now we are way under everyone.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uveldrindel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Veldrindel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/19/01 11:37:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1375.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: why cant we....</span><hr size=1> Regarding damage output comparisons across classes, I think you should be able to pay for better/higher/easier/whatever offense with worse/lower/harder/whatever defense.  You can sort of lump together everything that goes into that balance: the amount of damage you do, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> how</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> you do your damage, the risk you take to do the damage, the time it takes to do that damage, the amount of armor or other defenses you can use, the amount of damage you can take, etc; and make it into an overly simplified pool of 10 points.  Then you can allocate those 10 points to either offense or defense.  <br>
<br>
For instance, your average nuking fingerwaggler can do a lot of damage from a distance, but can't take much damage if they let the foe get to them before they kill it.  They'd be like a 9 offense, 1 defense.  Whereas your theoretical tank should average out around 5 offense, 5 defense (maybe 6 offense, 4 defense or 4 offense, 6 defense depending on what gear or skills they choose to use, but you get the picture).  Steady damage dealing and taking.<br>
<br>
Now, considering the first post of this thread, let's compare an archer and an assassin.  The archer can do a lot of damage from a distance.  I believe that someplace Mythic stated that an archer should ideally be able to knock off 1/2 to 3/4 of the target's life before it reaches them, then they finish it off with melee.  They should be 3/4 ranged, 1/4 melee, basically.  They train one skill, archery, to do that 1/2 to 3/4 damage and shouldn't be hit by the target while doing it.  Once they get to melee, they get reinforced armor (less than a tank, but better than a nuker) to protect themselves and have fewer hitpoints than a tank, but more than a nuker.  Let's give them 7 offense, 3 defense.<br>
<br>
In order for assassins to do their damage, they have to sneak up unseen and once they fire off that first hit, they begin taking damage from the target and are in melee.  In order to do that damage, they have to train <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> two</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> skills, CS and Stealth, and it takes longer to slowly sneak in and position themselves perfectly for the Critical Strike.  Therefore, their damage is more difficult to deal out than the archer (or nuker) who just has to get in range and firefirefire or the tank that just has to walk up and start whacking.  Finally, assassins get armor between archers and nukers.  Theoretically, they should then be rated around 8 offense, 2 defense.  Ideally, assassins should be able to knock off <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> at least</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 1/2 to 3/4 of the target's life before having to engage it in normal melee.<br>
<br>
In other words, in this scheme the assassin's level appropriate critical strike or critical strike chain (and we could even add in level appropriate poison to the equation which would add a third skill that would have to be worked on to do our optimum damage) should do a level of damage higher than an archer's critical shot + normal shots until the mob reaches them but lower than the amount a nuker can nuke a mob for before it reaches them.<br>
<br>
As Mythic stated, the assassin classes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be the most challenging to play, but that challenge should come from having to tactically set up the situation to be able to deal our damage and do our jobs, not from having an increased cost and risk in order to do mediocre damage.  As I said, this scheme is overly simplified, but hopefully it instills a general sense of what I'm talking about. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/umaiyasamsara.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maiya Samsara</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Safehouse Supporter</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(12/20/01 12:05:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1375.topic&index=18>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Archers are hardly overpowered</span><hr size=1> Archers are the only ones I regularly kill. Even orange archers. Now, if I'm underpowered, but can consistantly kill archers without ever dying to one how are they overpowered?<br>
